## Example 4 — Find the Area of a Circle Containing a Sector

Find the area of the circle that contains each sector. Round to the nearest tenth, if necessary.

### Step 1: Use the Sector Area Formula in Reverse

If a sector has area A and central angle x, the whole circle area can be found:
[
A_circle = A_sector * (360/x)
]

### Step 2: Verify with Radius if Possible

If the sector's radius is known, you can also use [A = pi * r^2] directly.

One sector has an area of 210 square centimeters and arc measure of 30 degrees.
[
A_circle = 210 * (360/30)
]
[
A_circle = 210 * 12
]
[
A_circle = 2520 cm^2
]

One sector has an area of 65 square feet and arc measure of 270 degrees.
[
A_circle = 65 * (360/270)
]
[
A_circle = 65 * (4/3)
]
[
A_circle = 86.7 ft^2
]

One sector has an area of 325 square millimeters and arc measure of 72 degrees.
[
A_circle = 325 * (360/72)
]
[
A_circle = 325 * 5
]
[
A_circle = 1625 mm^2
]

One sector has an area of 167 square inches and arc measure of 110 degrees.
[
A_circle = 167 * (360/110)
]
[
A_circle = 167 * 3.27
]
[
A_circle = 546.1 in^2
]

One sector has an area of 98 square meters and arc measure of 40 degrees.
[
A_circle = 98 * (360/40)
]
[
A_circle = 98 * 9
]
[
A_circle = 882 m^2
]

One sector has an area of 412 square inches and arc measure of 82 degrees.
[
A_circle = 412 * (360/82)
]
[
A_circle = 412 * 4.39
]
[
A_circle = 1808.7 in^2
